970s to today's continuing conflict. The author examines the influence they exercised through composing and reciting poems and songs, informal speech and other symbolic acts, and analysestheir impact in the social and political domains. Challenging the pervasive portrayal of women as natural peacebuilders and their roles as passive and submissive, the author highlights how Sudan's state government co-opted al-Hakkamat Baggara women to lobby on its behalf, to rally for war and to advocate for peace. Understanding how they can contribute to the resolution and resettlement processes is vital to sustainable reconciliation and post-conflict transformation of the unstable state. Suad M.E. Musa (PhD) is a Freelance Consultant on gender and women's issues. She worked with the government of Sudan and with CSOs and INGOs in the Horn of Africa and Britain. She alsoworked as Assistant Professor of Sociology at Qatar University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBaggara (African people)zSudanzDarfur. 0aMuslim womenzSudanzDarfur. 0aWomen, ArabzSudanzDarfur. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aDarfur.  aSudan.  aconflict in Sudan.  awar in Sudan.  awomen and peacekeeping.  awomen and war.  awomen in Africa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787442320?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787442320423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787442320/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles